P(A and B) = P(A) * P(B|A)

Where P(B|A) is the probability of B given A. Since P(B|A) is a probability, it must be less than or equal to 1. Therefore:

P(A and B) ≤ P(A)

In other words, the probability of both A and B occurring together (option b) must be less than or equal to the probability of just A occurring (option a). So option (b) cannot be more likely than option (a).
